I found this old 538 article that analyzed the predictiveness of early polling in Senate campaigns (https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/early-senate-polls-have-plenty-to-tell-us-about-november/). Average error between average of early polls and final vote share was 6.4 percentage points. Let's say 6.  Right now Cunningham is leading Tillis by four points, with an average MoE (I know that's not how you do this) of about 3. I know that the MoE is 2*s.e., but let's just use it as the s.d. of my belief distribution for now -- add some uncertainty. So supposing my beliefs about Cunningham's final vote share are distributed N(44,3) and my beliefs about Thillis's are distributed N(40,3), then my beliefs about the difference Cunningham - Thillis are distributed roughly N(4, 4). So 84% of my distribution lies above 0. This seems a little overconfident to me so I round down to 80. Let's try it the other way, per 538. Supposing Cunningham's final vote share is between 38 and 50, that Thillis's final vote share is between 34 and 46. Suppose a uniform distribution over both sets of values. What does that get us? In all permutations of these figures, Cunningham beats Thillis in 73% of cases. So I split the difference.

1. Looking at the last ~40 years, Republican senators have won elections about 75% of the time
2. In the same time period, when a Republican incumbent is running, they have been reelected about 2/3rds of the time
3. This gives me a naive prior of about 70% expecting Republican candidate (Thillis) to win
4. Probably worth noting that when a senatorial race has coincided with a presidential election (again last ~40 years), the result has been same party winning about 70% of the time, so this could be as much a referendum on the president as about anything else
5. Yes there are a lot of positive signs for Democrats right now, both in opinion polls as well as approval ratings, but there is a lot of recency bias at the moment with COVID, and still a lot of uncertainty between now and November
6. In light of current polling numbers (both Senatorial as well as on presidential candidates as per fivethirtyeight links previously shared by others), am adjusting prior downwards 5% in favour of Democrats
